    notes:
      "## The WADA Banned Status — Read This First\nPhenylpiracetam is **on the WADA Prohibited List** (Category S6 stimulants). For any user with potential drug-testing exposure (Olympic athletes, NCAA athletes, professional sports, military personnel, certain employment contexts), phenylpiracetam use produces positive tests and rule violations.\n\nHistorical context: phenylpiracetam (carphedon) was central to the Russian doping scandal that led to multiple athlete suspensions. It's specifically tested for in Olympic and professional sports contexts.\n\nFor non-athletes without drug-testing exposure, this caveat doesn't apply — phenylpiracetam is legal in the US under DSHEA as a nootropic supplement. But the WADA status is the first thing to verify before use.\n\n## The Cycling Discipline — The Central Success Factor\nUnlike most other racetams (and most nootropics generally), phenylpiracetam develops tolerance rapidly with daily use. Within ~3 weeks of daily dosing, the stimulant-like effects substantially diminish; users often respond by escalating dose, which produces minimal additional effect and increases side effects without restoring full efficacy.\n\n**The only way to maintain phenylpiracetam's effects is strict cycling.** Practical cycling protocols:\n\n**Standard cycle:** 3–5 days on / 3–5 days off. Most common protocol; sustainable for chronic use across many months.\n\n**Single-event dosing:** 100mg the morning of high-stakes events (presentations, exams, races). Most discipline-light approach; phenylpiracetam used as occasional performance tool rather than daily supplement.\n\n**Short-burst protocol:** 100mg BID × 5–7 days for intense work periods (project deadlines, exam weeks, training camps), followed by 2+ weeks off. Useful for cyclic high-demand contexts.\n\n**What doesn't work:** daily continuous use beyond 3 weeks. Tolerance is essentially complete; only washout restores responsiveness.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n100mg AM single dose × first day to assess tolerance and effect profile. If well-tolerated and effects are valued, transition to cycled use (3–5 days on / 3–5 days off, OR single-event dosing). **Pair with Alpha-GPC 300mg or CDP-Choline 250mg from the start** to prevent racetam headache. Track: cognitive function, energy, focus, motivation, sleep quality (PM dosing produces insomnia for most users — strict AM dosing required), mood.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**Single-event peak performance protocol:** Phenylpiracetam 100mg + Alpha-GPC 300mg + caffeine 100–200mg (modest) + L-theanine 200mg, all 60–90 minutes before high-stakes event. The combination addresses cognitive enhancement (phenylpiracetam + Alpha-GPC), arousal (caffeine), and over-stimulation modulation (L-theanine). Single-use only; not for daily protocols.\n\n**Multi-racetam comprehensive cognitive stack (advanced users):** Aniracetam 750mg BID (continuous, anxiolytic + AMPA PAM) + Phenylpiracetam 100mg cycled (3 days on / 4 days off, dopaminergic stimulant) + Alpha-GPC 600mg/day (substrate) + Lion's Mane 1000mg/day. The multi-racetam approach uses complementary mechanisms; the Aniracetam continuous + Phenylpiracetam cycled pattern provides baseline cognitive support with periodic stimulant-like enhancement.\n\n## Phenylpiracetam vs Adderall — Honest Comparison\nUsers sometimes consider phenylpiracetam as an Adderall alternative for ADHD-like cognitive needs. The honest comparison:\n\n**Phenylpiracetam vs Adderall:**\n- **Effect magnitude:** Adderall is more potent for ADHD focus/attention\n- **Cardiovascular profile:** phenylpiracetam typically milder\n- **Tolerance:** phenylpiracetam develops tolerance faster than Adderall; both develop tolerance with daily use\n- **Dependence:** Adderall has Schedule II controlled substance status with addiction concerns; phenylpiracetam has lower abuse potential\n- **Regulatory:** Adderall is prescription; phenylpiracetam is OTC nootropic in US (but WADA-banned for athletes)\n- **Diagnosis context:** Adderall use without ADHD diagnosis raises clinical concerns; phenylpiracetam doesn't have this regulatory framework\n\nFor users with diagnosed ADHD where prescription therapy is appropriate: Adderall, methylphenidate, or other prescribed treatments are the right path. For users wanting occasional cognitive enhancement without ADHD context: phenylpiracetam (cycled) may fit but isn't a true Adderall replacement for clinical cognitive impairment.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule, tablet, or powder. **Strict AM dosing — PM dosing produces insomnia for most users.** With or without food acceptable.\n\n## Synergies\n**Alpha-GPC / CDP-Choline:** racetam + choline donor pairing — prevents headache. **Aniracetam:** complementary racetam (continuous baseline + cycled stimulant pattern). **L-theanine:** modulates over-stimulation; useful for anxious users or in single-event peak performance protocols. **Caffeine:** additive arousal effect; combinations modest dosing. **Lion's Mane:** complementary cognitive mechanism.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nThe English-language clinical evidence base is limited; most phenylpiracetam research was published in Russian. Russian clinical trials covered cognitive disorders (post-stroke, vascular cognitive impairment), asthenia (chronic fatigue), and depression — generally supportive for the indications. Western nootropic community use is largely empirical / anecdotal rather than RCT-validated.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism partially characterized. Russian clinical use establishes pharmaceutical-grade safety profile and efficacy in specific clinical contexts. English-language RCT evidence limited. Long real-world use in Russian medical practice (~30 years as Phenotropil) provides general safety baseline.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid Russian clinical use base; mechanism partially characterized (dopaminergic + cholinergic + glutamatergic); English-language RCT evidence limited. Anecdote: extensive use in nootropic and biohacking communities for stimulant-like cognitive enhancement; subjective effects strong (often more pronounced than other nootropics); cycling discipline matters substantially. Decision frame: distinct from other racetams (stimulant-like profile rather than pure cognitive enhancement); useful for high-stakes performance contexts (single-event dosing); WADA-banned status is the first regulatory check; cycling discipline is mandatory for sustained efficacy; not appropriate for users with cardiovascular concerns, anxiety disorders, or substance use disorder history.",
